%S A395769 1,2,2,4,6,4,8,8,6,12,10,8,14,16,12,16,16,12,18,24,16,20,24,16,30,28,
%T A395769 18,32,30,24,32,32,20,32,48,24,38,36,28,48,40,32,42,40,36,48,48,32,56,
%U A395769 60,32,56,54,36,60,64,36,60,58,48,62,64,48,64,84,40,66,64,48,96
%N A395769 The twisted Euler phi-function for the Dirichlet character kronecker(-8,.) mod 8.
%C A395769 We have h(-8*n^2), the class number of the order of Z[sqrt(-2)] with discriminant -8*n^2, is equal to a(n).
%C A395769 In general, let d < 0 be a fundamental discriminant and n be a positive integer such that d*n^2 < -4, then h(d*n^2) = L(0,kronecker(d,.)) * n * Product_{p|n, p prime} (1 - kronecker(d,p)/p). This is a combination of Theorem 7.24 in "Primes of the form x^2+ny^2" by Cox and the Dirichlet class number formula. Here L(0,kronecker(-8,.)) = 1.
%D A395769 D. A. Cox, Primes of the form x^2+ny^2, Wiley, New York, 1989, p. 146.
%H A395769 Jianing Song, <a href="/A395769/b395769.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%F A395769 Multiplicative with a(2^e) = 2^e, a(p^e) = p^(e-1)*(p-1) if p == 1, 3 (mod 8) and a(p^e) = p^(e-1)*(p+1) if p == 3, 5 (mod 8).
%e A395769 Given L(0,kronecker(-8,.)) = 1, we have: h(-8*1^2) = a(1) = 1, h(-8*2^2) = a(2) = 2, h(-8*3^2) = a(3) = 2, h(-8*4^2) = a(4) = 4, ...
%o A395769 (PARI) a(n,{d=-8}) = my(f=factor(n)[,1]~, w=#f); n * prod(i=1, w, 1 - kronecker(d,f[i])/f[i])
%Y A395769 A188510 is the corresponding Dirichlet character.
%Y A395769 Cf. for fundamental discriminants -3..-24: A227128, A395768, A395771, this sequence, A395772, A395773, A395774, A395775, A395776, A395777.
%K A395769 nonn,easy,mult,new
%O A395769 1,2
